AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; The Cdr of AGI, the FNSI and the Roman Press consider "gravely detrimental to the professionalism and tertiousness demonstrated in the decades by the journalists of the test the statement made to the question time by the Minister of Economy, Giancarlo Giorgetti, according to which "it is a delicate question that a society participated from the State possesses a press agency, as this could fuel doubts on the same freedom of actual information.
&nbsp;
In the 70 years of AGI history within a state participation such as Eni, held in part directly by Mef himself, "the agency and its chroniclers have proven to be a free and independent information presidium with any of the many governmental majorities that have occurred over time."
&nbsp;
Giorgetti also argued that the Mef "would demand the maximization of the economic value of an eventual alienation", also taking into account "the fact that the press agencies are assigned considerations by the State" and that "the procedures must meet the requirements of transparency, be competitive, and obviously ensure occupational levels".
&nbsp;
Precisely "the absence of transparency in this operation" has been underlined by the CoR, the FNSI and the Roman Press in every passage of a dispute that will see them engaged "with even greater determination in the coming hours, along with the editing assembly, in the defense of the autonomy and independence of the Agi and pluralism of information". In these days - the Cdr dell'Agi, the FNSI and the Roman Printing - "have been called into question regarding the operation several Authority: Anac, Antitrust, Agcom. The dossier, given the delicacy and severity of the transparency profiles it invests, has come to the European Commission"

